      "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "A vibratory conveyor moves material along a trough or tube using controlled vibration instead of a belt, chain, or roller. An electromagnetic, electromechanical, or pneumatic drive generates rapid oscillations (typically 1,800-3,600 cycles per minute) that propel material in micro-hops along the conveying surface. Vibratory conveyors handle bulk solids including powders, granules, pellets, and small parts with gentle, consistent material flow and zero moving parts in the product zone." }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What is the difference between a vibratory conveyor and a vibratory feeder?",
      "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "A vibratory conveyor moves material over a distance (typically 3-30 feet). A vibratory feeder meters material at a controlled rate from a hopper or bin onto a conveyor, scale, or process machine. Feeders prioritize volumetric or gravimetric accuracy. Conveyors prioritize throughput and distance. Many systems combine both: a vibratory feeder meters material from a hopper onto a vibratory conveyor that transports it to the next process." }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What is a vibratory bowl feeder?",
      "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "A vibratory bowl feeder is a circular vibratory device that orients and feeds small discrete parts (fasteners, caps, electronic components) single-file to an assembly machine or packaging line. Parts dump into the bowl, and vibration drives them up a helical track inside the bowl. Tooling along the track rejects misoriented parts back into the bowl. Correctly oriented parts exit through a linear track to the downstream machine. Bowl feeders are essential in automated assembly and packaging." }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What materials can vibratory conveyors handle?",
      "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Vibratory conveyors handle a wide range of dry bulk solids including powders, granules, pellets, flakes, crystals, and small discrete parts. They suit food ingredients (sugar, flour, spices, nuts, snack foods), chemicals (pigments, resins, catalysts), pharmaceuticals (tablets, capsules), metal parts (fasteners, stampings), and recycled materials. Materials that are very sticky, wet, or highly cohesive may not flow well on vibratory conveyors without specialized trough treatments." }
    }
