---

<BaseLayout
  title="Vibratory Conveyors & Feeders: Electromagnetic, Electromechanical & Bowl Feeders"
  description="Complete guide to vibratory conveyors and feeders: electromagnetic, electromechanical, natural frequency drives. Bowl feeders, linear feeders, hopper systems for packaging and bulk handling."
  canonical="https://packagingconveyor.com/conveyor-types/vibratory-conveyors/"
  schema={[breadcrumbSchema, faqSchema, articleSchema]}
>

  <!-- Breadcrumb -->
  <nav class="bg-surface border-b border-border" aria-label="Breadcrumb">
    <div class="max-w-7xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8 py-3">
      <ol class="flex items-center gap-2 text-sm text-ink-muted">
        <li><a href="/" class="hover:text-accent transition-colors">Home</a></li>
        <li class="text-ink-muted/50">/</li>
        <li><a href="/conveyor-types/" class="hover:text-accent transition-colors">Conveyor Types</a></li>
        <li class="text-ink-muted/50">/</li>
        <li class="text-ink font-semibold">Vibratory Conveyors & Feeders</li>
      </ol>
    </div>
  </nav>

  <!-- AIO -->
  <section class="py-16 sm:py-20 bg-surface-dim bg-dots">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Vibratory Conveyors & Feeders</div>
      <h1 class="font-display text-5xl sm:text-6xl font-extrabold text-ink tracking-wide uppercase leading-tight mb-8">
        Vibratory Conveyors & Feeders
      </h1>
      <div class="text-xl text-ink-muted leading-relaxed max-w-3xl">
        <p>A vibratory conveyor moves material along a trough using controlled vibration. No belt, chain, or rollers contact the product. Electromagnetic, electromechanical, or pneumatic drives generate rapid oscillations (typically 1,800-3,600 cycles per minute) that propel bulk solids in micro-hops along the conveying surface. Vibratory feeders meter material from hoppers at precise rates, while vibratory bowl feeders orient and singulate small parts for automated assembly and <a href="/industries/packaging-line-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">packaging lines</a>. Together, vibratory conveyors and feeders handle everything from fine powders to heavy castings across food, pharmaceutical, chemical, and metalworking industries.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Drive Types -->
  <article class="py-20 bg-surface" aria-labelledby="drive-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Drive Technology</div>
      <h2 id="drive-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-extrabold text-ink tracking-wide mb-8">
        Vibratory Drive <span class="text-accent">Types</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-6">

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Electromagnetic Drives</h3>
        <p>Electromagnetic vibratory drives use an AC-powered electromagnet that attracts and releases a spring-loaded armature at line frequency (3,600 CPM at 60 Hz). The rapid cycling creates high-frequency, low-amplitude vibration. Electromagnetic drives offer instant start/stop, precise amplitude control via voltage adjustment, and no rotating parts. They excel in precision feeding applications where feed rate accuracy within 1-2% is required. Eriez, Syntron (Kadant), and FMC Technologies manufacture electromagnetic vibratory feeders and conveyors.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Electromechanical Drives</h3>
        <p>Electromechanical vibratory drives use rotating eccentric weights on motor shafts to generate vibration. Single-shaft units produce circular vibration. Dual-shaft units with counter-rotating weights produce linear (directional) vibration. Electromechanical drives produce higher amplitudes and greater force output than electromagnetic drives, making them suitable for heavier loads and longer conveying distances. Typical frequencies: 900-1,800 RPM. General Kinematics, Carrier Vibrating Equipment, and JOST manufacture electromechanical vibratory systems.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Natural Frequency (Tuned) Drives</h3>
        <p>Natural frequency vibratory conveyors operate at the system's resonant frequency, where spring energy stores and releases with minimal input power. A small drive force sustains large oscillation amplitudes because the system resonates. Natural frequency drives consume 60-80% less energy than brute-force electromechanical drives for the same throughput. They suit long-distance vibratory conveying (10-30+ feet) where energy efficiency matters. Adjusting the spring system tunes the natural frequency to match the drive frequency. General Kinematics' VIBRA-DRUM and Key Technology's Iso-Flo are natural frequency designs.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Pneumatic Drives</h3>
        <p>Pneumatic vibratory drives use compressed air to power a piston or turbine that generates vibration. They suit hazardous environments where electric motors pose ignition risks (grain dust, solvent vapors, combustible powder). Pneumatic drives are also used where washdown requirements make electrical drives impractical. They require compressed air infrastructure and consume more energy than electric drives, so they serve niche applications rather than general-purpose conveying.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>

  <!-- Equipment Types -->
  <section class="py-20 bg-surface-dim bg-dots" aria-labelledby="equipment-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Equipment Types</div>
      <h2 id="equipment-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-extrabold text-ink tracking-wide mb-8">
        Vibratory Equipment <span class="text-accent">Categories</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-6">

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Vibratory Bowl Feeders</h3>
        <p>Bowl feeders orient and singulate small discrete parts for automated assembly and packaging. Parts dump into a round bowl. Vibration drives them up a helical track machined or cast inside the bowl. Tooling along the track (wiper blades, air jets, profile cutouts) rejects misoriented parts back into the bowl. Correctly oriented parts exit through a linear inline track to the downstream machine. Bowl feeders handle fasteners, caps, closures, electronic components, medical device parts, and pharmaceutical capsules. RNA Automation, Performance Feeders, and Hoosier Feeder Company build custom bowl feeders.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Linear Vibratory Feeders</h3>
        <p>Linear feeders move material in a straight line from a hopper or bin outlet to a conveyor, scale, or process machine. An electromagnetic or electromechanical drive vibrates a trough at a controlled angle that propels material forward. Feed rate adjusts by changing vibration amplitude. Linear feeders meter powders, granules, and small parts with accuracy from 0.5-5% of setpoint. They serve as the interface between bulk storage and downstream processes in <a href="/industries/food-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">food</a>, pharmaceutical, and chemical packaging.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Vibratory Conveying Troughs</h3>
        <p>Vibratory troughs transport bulk materials over distances from 3 to 30+ feet. They replace belt conveyors where sanitation, product gentleness, or the need to perform screening/sorting during conveying justifies the higher cost. Troughs come in open and enclosed (tubular) configurations. Stainless steel troughs serve food and pharmaceutical applications. Carbon steel troughs serve mining, aggregate, and recycling. Key Technology, Eriez, and Carrier Vibrating Equipment manufacture vibratory conveying troughs.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Vibratory Screeners & Separators</h3>
        <p>Vibratory screeners combine conveying with size separation. Material travels across a vibrating screen deck, and undersize particles fall through the mesh while oversize particles continue along the deck. Single-deck screeners make one size cut. Multi-deck screeners make multiple cuts simultaneously. Vibratory screeners serve quality control in <a href="/conveyor-functions/reject-systems/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">reject and inspection</a> operations, removing oversized, undersized, and foreign materials from bulk product streams.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Vibratory Hoppers & Bin Activators</h3>
        <p>Vibratory hoppers and bin activators mount on storage bins and silos to promote material flow from the bin outlet. Many bulk materials (flour, sugar, powders, granules) bridge, rathole, or arch inside bins, stopping flow. Vibratory bin activators break these flow obstructions by vibrating the bin cone or outlet section. They work with vibratory feeders below the bin to create a reliable flow path from storage to process.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Comparison Table -->
  <section class="py-20 bg-surface" aria-labelledby="compare-heading">
