            <tr class="border-b border-border">
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 font-semibold text-ink">Frequency</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4">3,600 CPM (60 Hz)</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4">900-1,800 RPM</td>
              <td class="py-3">System-tuned</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="border-b border-border">
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 font-semibold text-ink">Amplitude</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4">Low (precision)</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4">High (heavy duty)</td>
              <td class="py-3">High (energy-efficient)</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="border-b border-border">
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 font-semibold text-ink">Feed Rate Control</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4">Excellent (&pm;1-2%)</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4">Good (&pm;3-5%)</td>
              <td class="py-3">Good (&pm;3-5%)</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="border-b border-border">
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 font-semibold text-ink">Conveying Distance</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4">Short (1-6 ft)</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4">Medium (3-20 ft)</td>
              <td class="py-3">Long (10-30+ ft)</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="border-b border-border">
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 font-semibold text-ink">Energy Efficiency</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4">Moderate</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4">Lower</td>
              <td class="py-3">Highest</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 font-semibold text-ink">Relative Cost</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 font-mono text-sm">$$</td>
              <td class="py-3 pr-4 font-mono text-sm">$$</td>
              <td class="py-3 font-mono text-sm">$$$</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <p class="text-sm text-ink-muted mt-4">Cost is relative within vibratory equipment category. See <a href="/resources/conveyor-cost-guide/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">conveyor cost guide</a> for pricing factors.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Applications -->
  <section class="py-20 bg-surface-dim bg-dots" aria-labelledby="apps-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Applications</div>
      <h2 id="apps-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-extrabold text-ink tracking-wide mb-8">
        Vibratory Conveyor <span class="text-accent">Applications</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-6">
        <p><strong class="text-ink">Food processing and packaging:</strong> Vibratory conveyors distribute snack foods, candy, nuts, cereal, and frozen foods from processing to weighing and packaging machines. The gentle vibration prevents product breakage. Stainless steel troughs meet <a href="/industries/food-conveyors/sanitary/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">sanitary requirements</a>. Vibratory distribution systems spread product evenly across multi-head combination weighers for accurate fill weights. Key Technology, Heat and Control, and Eriez supply vibratory distribution and conveying systems for food packaging.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">Pharmaceutical tablet handling:</strong> Vibratory feeders meter tablets and capsules from bulk containers to counting machines, bottle fillers, and blister packaging lines. The gentle conveying action minimizes tablet chipping and dust generation. Enclosed vibratory tubes contain dust and prevent cross-contamination between products. Electromagnetic drives provide the precise feed rate control required for pharmaceutical accuracy.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">Parts feeding for assembly:</strong> Bowl feeders orient and singulate caps, closures, fasteners, springs, O-rings, and electronic components for automated assembly machines. Each bowl feeder is custom-tooled for the specific part geometry. A typical automated assembly machine uses multiple bowl feeders, one for each component type. <a href="/conveyor-types/cleated-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">Cleated belt elevators</a> often feed bulk parts into bowl feeder hoppers.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">Mining and aggregate screening:</strong> Vibratory screeners classify crushed stone, sand, gravel, and mineral ore by particle size. Multi-deck vibrating screens produce multiple size fractions in a single pass. Vibratory conveyors feed material to screens and transport separated fractions to stockpiles or downstream processing. General Kinematics, Carrier, and Metso manufacture mining-grade vibratory screening equipment.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">Recycling and waste:</strong> Vibratory conveyors and screeners sort recycled materials by size and density. Vibratory flat-deck separators remove fines (dirt, glass fragments) from mixed recyclables before manual or optical sorting. Vibratory feeders meter shredded material onto sorting conveyors at controlled rates for consistent sorting quality.</p>

        <p><strong class="text-ink">Foundry and metalworking:</strong> Vibratory conveyors transport hot castings, forgings, and stampings from production to cooling and cleaning operations. The vibration action helps remove sand from castings (shakeout). Vibratory troughs can handle temperatures up to 1,000&deg;F with heat-resistant steel construction. General Kinematics manufactures vibratory shakeout and cooling systems for foundries.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Design & Specification -->
  <section class="py-20 bg-surface" aria-labelledby="spec-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Specification</div>
      <h2 id="spec-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-extrabold text-ink tracking-wide mb-8">
        Design <span class="text-accent">Considerations</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-6">

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Material Flow Characteristics</h3>
        <p>Material bulk density, particle size distribution, moisture content, and angle of repose determine vibratory conveyor sizing and drive selection. Free-flowing materials (dry sand, pellets, sugar) convey easily. Cohesive materials (wet powder, sticky granules) require higher amplitude, steeper trough angles, or anti-stick coatings. Extremely fine powders may aerosolize and require enclosed tubular designs.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Trough Design</h3>
        <p>Trough cross-sections include flat-bottom, round-bottom, V-bottom, and tubular. Flat-bottom troughs suit general conveying. Round-bottom troughs promote material flow and resist buildup. V-bottom troughs center material flow for discharge to a centered point. Tubular designs enclose the material completely, preventing dust emissions and contamination. Trough width determines volumetric capacity. Standard widths: 4" to 48".</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Isolation & Mounting</h3>
        <p>Vibratory equipment generates dynamic forces that transmit to the supporting structure if not properly isolated. Spring mounts (coil springs, rubber springs, or air springs) isolate the vibrating trough from the building structure. Isolation efficiency should exceed 90% to prevent building vibration, structural fatigue, and noise. Vibratory conveyors should not be hard-mounted to mezzanines, platforms, or building steel without engineering review of the dynamic loading.</p>

        <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink">Noise</h3>
        <p>Vibratory equipment generates 80-95 dBA noise levels depending on frequency, amplitude, material type, and trough construction. Noise-sensitive environments require sound enclosures, dampening trough liners, or lower-frequency natural frequency drives (which produce less noise than high-frequency electromagnetic drives). OSHA requires hearing protection above 85 dBA for 8-hour time-weighted average exposure.</p>
        <!-- VERIFY: Noise levels 80-95 dBA against Eriez, Syntron, and General Kinematics published specifications -->
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- FAQ -->
  <section class="py-20 bg-surface-dim bg-dots" aria-labelledby="faq-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <h2 id="faq-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-extrabold text-ink tracking-wide mb-10">
        Frequently Asked <span class="text-accent">Questions</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="space-y-4">
        <details class="group border border-border bg-surface p-6 open:pb-8" open>
          <summary class="font-display text-xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between group-open:mb-4">
            What is a vibratory conveyor?
            <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-ink-muted group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform flex-shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" /></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-3">
            <p>A vibratory conveyor moves material through controlled vibration instead of belts, chains, or rollers. Electromagnetic, electromechanical, or pneumatic drives generate oscillations that propel bulk solids in micro-hops along a trough. Zero moving parts contact the product, making vibratory conveyors ideal for sanitary and gentle-handling applications.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="group border border-border bg-surface p-6 open:pb-8">
          <summary class="font-display text-xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between group-open:mb-4">
            Vibratory conveyor vs. vibratory feeder?
            <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-ink-muted group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform flex-shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" /></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-3">
            <p>A conveyor transports material over distance (3-30+ ft). A feeder meters material at a controlled rate from a hopper or bin. Feeders prioritize rate accuracy. Conveyors prioritize throughput and distance. Many systems combine both: a feeder meters from storage, and a conveyor transports to the next process.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="group border border-border bg-surface p-6 open:pb-8">
          <summary class="font-display text-xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between group-open:mb-4">
            What is a vibratory bowl feeder?
            <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-ink-muted group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform flex-shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" /></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-3">
            <p>A round vibratory device with a helical track inside. Parts dump into the bowl, vibration drives them up the track, and tooling along the track rejects misoriented parts. Correctly oriented parts exit single-file to the downstream machine. Essential for automated assembly of caps, fasteners, and electronic components.</p>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="group border border-border bg-surface p-6 open:pb-8">
          <summary class="font-display text-xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between group-open:mb-4">
            What materials can vibratory conveyors handle?
            <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-ink-muted group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform flex-shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" /></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-3">
            <p>Most dry bulk solids: powders, granules, pellets, flakes, crystals, and small parts. Food ingredients, chemicals, pharmaceuticals, metal parts, and recyclables. Very sticky, wet, or highly cohesive materials may require specialized trough coatings or higher-amplitude drives.</p>
          </div>
        </details>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Related -->
  <section class="py-16 bg-ink-light" aria-labelledby="related-heading">
    <div class="max-w-7xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <div class="section-label text-accent-bright mb-4">Related Pages</div>
      <h2 id="related-heading" class="font-display text-3xl font-extrabold text-white tracking-wide mb-8">Continue <span class="text-accent-bright">Researching</span></h2>
      <div class="grid sm:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-4 gap-4">
        <a href="/conveyor-types/pneumatic-conveyors/" class="p-5 border border-white/10 bg-white/[0.03] hover:bg-white/[0.06] hover:border-accent/40 transition-all group">
          <div class="font-display text-lg font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-white group-hover:text-accent-bright transition-colors mb-1">Pneumatic Conveyors</div>
          <p class="text-sm text-white/60">Enclosed powder transport</p>
        </a>
        <a href="/conveyor-types/trough-conveyors/" class="p-5 border border-white/10 bg-white/[0.03] hover:bg-white/[0.06] hover:border-accent/40 transition-all group">
